"Another big thanks from 2BDChicago for the never ending Secret Santa haul. 12oz. bottle served in my SA Perfect Pint at 53 degrees. Pours the color and clarity of cola with a loose, half inch, fizzy, khaki-colored head that sizzles and pops as it dissipates into a consistent quarter inch froth. Swaths and spatters of lacing coat the walls of the class during the tasting. Nose expresses earthy/piny hops in the foreground and a suggestion of chocolate malt in the background. Taste consistent with nose; however, there's a slightly metallic quality in the middle and the malt profile is very much subdued. Mouthfeel is light-medium with a prickly carbonation that leaves a residual burn at the back of the throat. There's also a little bit of acidity that lightly stimulates the sides of the cheeks. Overall, a pretty good representation of the style; however, I prefer something a bit more malt forward. Well worth your time if the opportunity presents and you tastes lean towards the hoppier end of the spectrum."
""
"O: The bottle lists this as a Black IPA, so that is what I'll rate it as. Sure this one is packed full of charred malts and citrus hops, but there is no balance between the two. Actually there is disharmony and, while this beer isn't a bad beer, I'm just not feeling the love from it either."
"M - Medium body with moderate carbonation."
"Pours extremely dark amber. The red coloring only shows when held up to light. Not much of a head here. Holy shit, great scent! Piney hops right in your face, but not enough to think you're going to drink Pine-Sol. Mouth watering. The hops are definitely up front on this one. It finishes up sweet, and I wonder if that's the molasses they said was in it on the bottle. Another great effort from New Glarus. Cheers!"
"O - I am pretty critical of these new ABAs and prefer an opaque black color, huge hoppy nose, and as little dark malts as possible. This beer is not that dark, not that hoppy and a little on the malty side but these standards are nearly unreachable. I prefer Lakefront brewing companys IBA to this but this is an excellent interpretation of a new style that my guidelines might be construed against. Still another great beer from Wisconsin!!! New Glarus is great."
